\epigraph{Mother Nature doesn't care if you're having fun.}{Larry Niven}
%\epigraph{Fortune is of sluggish growth, but ruin is rapid.}{Lucius Annaeus Seneca}

The left-hand side of Equation \ref{eq:IPARC} is impact $I$ on the environment.
While there are natural processes that have (some) negative impacts on the environment,
such as volcanic eruptions and wild fires, this book is primarily concerned with
human impacts to the environment.
Greenhouse gas emissions, such as CO$_2$, are our prime example.
Other examples of human impact include deforestation, desertification, 
aquifer depletion, plant and animal extinctions, ground water and soil 
contamination, ozone depletion, smog creation, habitat destruction, and many other 
``tions.''

Chapter \ref{chap:introduction} pointed out the problems of exponential growth.
But why? Why is continued exponential growth impossible?
The reason is that we live on a finite planet with finite resources and finite boundaries.
Continued and greater impacts eventually run up against the Earth's finite boundaries.
Section \ref{sec:exp} shows that, for exponential growth, the ``eventually'' is
one doubling time.
In $ln(2)/r$ time units, the system will go from half its ``budget'' to being
at the limit, despite many, many previous doublings.
Part of the curse of exponential growth is that the end seems sudden.
This chapter explores those boundaries -- the ``budget,'' or carrying capacity, 
of the planet.
Exceeding Earth's carrying capacity degrades its ability to support life.

\section{Ecosystem services} 
\label{sec:ecosystem_services}
The Earth's ecosystems support life on Earth. Collectively, these supports are 
called \emph{ecosystem services}.
The first group of services are \emph{provisioning services}, which are material 
and energy resources.
For example, humans plant crops (food, textile, and timber) that ``grow,''
they're not manufactured. 
The ecosystem ``provides'' the crops. 
Likewise, the ecosystem provides water, petroleum, and other mineral resources.
Simply having oceans and an atmosphere \emph{provides} a place for pollution to go.

The second set of services is \emph{regulating and supporting services}, 
which sustain and stabilize the ecosystem, including 
processes for breaking down and recycling dead organisms; 
the carbon cycle; %(see Figure~\ref{fig:CCycle}),  
nitrogen, oxygen, and water cycles; 
and the fact that plant roots stabilize soil and prevent erosion.

The third set of services is \emph{cultural services}, 
which include recreation and literary and cultural inspiration.
Artists can't paint or take photographs of a landscape that isn't there.
Mountains and snow enable downhill skiing. 
Ocean waves enable surfing.
Rivers and lakes enable boating and (recreational) fishing opportunities.

Many international groups have examined the state of Earth's ecosystem services. 
The Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (MA) is a UN-affiliated group that studied ecosystem
services between 2001 and 2005. 
1300 authors from 95 countries were involved in authoring their findings. 
The MA found that (even back then) 15 out of the 24 ecosystem services 
they examined were being degraded or used unsustainably \cite{MA2005}.
%Most heavily affected are inland waters by decline in water quality and fragmentation of wetlands.

One way to think about ecosystem services is as \emph{natural capital}. 
``Capital'' refers to an improvement or building that is economically productive 
or valuable (see Chapter \ref{chap:affluence}).
The ecosystem produces value for human society by producing many things we use 
and disposing of many of our wastes.
Just as concepts of value and ownership motivate individuals and organizations
to care for and manage their capital stocks, there have been many attempts to classify
and value natural capital. 
Examples include:
\begin{itemize}
\item The European Environmental Agency's Common International Classification of
Ecosystem Services \cite{CICES2018} (which, incidentally, recognizes many more 
categories of ecosystem services than does the MA). 
\item The US Environmental Protection Agency's Final Ecosystem Goods and Services scoping tool.
\item The United Nations Statistical Division System of Environmental and Economic Accounting.
\item The Economics of Ecosystems and Biodiversity.
\end{itemize}

