Various analogies have been used to describe the benefits that ecosystem services provide, 
particularly in terms of the loss of a piece of the ecosystem. 
For example, the ecosystem is like an airplane.
When one rivet is lost, the result is not immediately catastrophic but accumulated 
losses can result in catastrophic failure. 
Alternatively, species are like individual stocks in a portfolio, where a wide diversity 
of species minimizes risk or volatility of return.

\section{Tipping points}
\label{sec:tipping}
