Drastic or catastrophic changes to ecosystems are not new or solely a modern problem.
Rapa Nui (Easter Island), the Levant, and the Sahara Desert have all undergone 
dramatic ecological shifts, although the degree to which this is attributable to 
human actions is not agreed upon or well understood \cite{Malhi2018}. 
Population-driven deforestation was a problem in ancient times and it remains so 
today. 
In places as far flung as Scandinavia \cite{Oestlund2015},
the Mayan empire \cite{Douglas2018}, southern Iran \cite{NFMiller1985}, but 
especially well documented in Mediterranean in the Greek- and Roman-era \cite{Hughes2011} 
is the overconsumption of wood for fuel and building and the clearing of forests 
to feed a growing population. 
The result was a permanent loss of soil fertility, erosion, and economic decline.

