What \emph{is} new is scope or magnitude of humanity's ability to affect the environment,
both due to high population and our level of technology.
Fossil-fuel derived carbon emissions are of particular concern.
Further examples include nuclear and industrial ``accidents,'' such as the Thule air-base crash,
the Palomares crash, the Seveso dioxin release, and, more recently, the Chernobyl
and Fukishima diasters, which have each contaminated many square kilometers.
Finally, %while the risk is, perhaps, less acute than it once was, 
a global thermonuclear war would be a humanitarian and environmental disaster on a 
truly global scale.

Equation \ref{eq:IPARC} frames sustainability in terms of ``impacts,'' that is, 
negative effects on the environment resulting from human activity. 
Broadly, there are two approaches for managing or responding to impacts. 
\emph{Planetary boundaries} describe the maximum (desirable) \emph{level} of effects,
that is, they establish a limit on the left-hand side of Equation \ref{eq:IPARC}.
The second method uses a weighted average, called an \emph{index}, of factors as 
a proxy management tool. 
The index describes a collection of behaviors. 
Whereas the planetary boundaries are limits for single variables, indices are a mix
of variables from both sides of Equation \ref{eq:IPARC}.
Neither method describes \emph{how} changes should be made but within each index
is an implicit description of the tradeoffs between the different variables. 
