Figure \ref{fig:GAfig21} is a conceptual representation of the relationship between
limits or boundaries and human effects on the environment. 
In part (a), there is no effective limit; human growth can continue unimpeded. 
However, Section \ref{sec:exp} shows that growth can't continue forever on a finite 
planet; there is always an eventual limit. 
In part (b), the boundary is hard and can never be crossed. 
For instance, the extractable fraction of a mineral in the Earth's crust can't, 
by definition, exceed 100\%. 
In part (c), exceeding the boundary is possible, for short times, but the boundary 
is robust. That is, it recovers. 
Renewable resources like grazing land, fisheries, timber, and aquifers \emph{may}
have behavior like this. 
Lastly, in part (d), exceeding the boundary causes long-term reduction in the 
capacity of the ecosystem to provide ecosystem services. 
As above, renewable resources like grazing land, fisheries, timber, and aquifers
\emph{can} have this behavior if their capacity is exceeded to much or for too long.
Alternatively, complex systems, like temperature regulation of the planet, may exhibit
tipping points that can radically change limits to an ecosystem service when the 
limit is exceeded. 
Carbon dioxide in the atmosphere is thought/feared to be an example
of this sort of behavior; when CO$_2$ increases too much, Earth will get 
\emph{dramatically} hotter, fundamentally altering many of its basic systems.

\section{Indices for sustainability}
\label{sec:indices}
There are many, many indices used to express or measure sustainability. 
All indices are, essentially, (weighted) averages of quantities related to
one or more of the three pillars shown in Figure \ref{fig:venn_diagram}.
% \subsection{Indices for environmental impact}
% \subsection{Indices for the economy}
% \subsection{Indices for social change}
Example indices include carbon footprint, ecological footprint (in global hectares
per person), and the human development index (HDI). 
Figure~\ref{fig:FootprintHDIGraph} plots ecological footprint and HDI for many 
different countries. 

% \begin{figure}
% \centering
% \includegraphics[width=\figwidth]{chapters/ch02-Boundaries/figures/EcoHDI.jpg}
% \caption{The ecological footprint per person and human development index for many nations.}
% \label{fig:ecofootprintHDI}
% \end{figure}

In contrast to planetary boundaries, which are hard biophysical limits, indices 
typically represent aggregated behavior. 
Aggregation allows grouping together of things that are different, for example, 
in the HDI, life expectancy at birth, expected years of schooling, and gross national income. 
Another example is the CO$_2$ equivalents, which expresses the global warming 
potential of various gases such as methane, nitrous oxide, and fluorinated gases
in terms of the amount of carbon dioxide that would give the same amount of warming,
disregarding any other environmental effects.

Indices and biophysical limits, such as planetary boundaries, exist to guide 
decision making. 
The weightings inherent in indices express preferences for tradeoffs among the 
different variables. 
Furthermore, having expressed an intent or preference for a certain limit, index, 
or behavior, these variables do not inherently generate strategies for achieving 
the goals or enforcement mechanisms for maintaining behavior. 
It remains for scientists, policy makers, and government officials to conduct 
research, make recommendations, regulate, and enforce laws.

