% see http://clivebest.com/blog/?p=1169 and references therein.
Here's a brief description of how climate change is happening. 
In the $\beta$ version of the text, this description will be made more complete.
If the radiation received from the sun exceeds the radiation given off by the Earth,
the Earth's temperature will increase. 
Increasing temperatures increases the amount of radiation given off by the Earth.
Eventually, a new equilibrium will be achieved. 
Radiation received from the sun is relatively constant; there are a variety of 
satellited-based and Earth-bound measurement systems to confirm this. 
Because the sun is very hot, the radiation it emits is high energy (short wave length).
Greenhouse gases, of which CO$_2$ is of chief concern, do not absorb these
short wave lengths. 
Radiation from the Earth is low energy (long wave length) because the Earth's
surface temperature is much lower than the Sun's.
CO$_2$ \emph{does} absorb energy at these wavelengths.
The lower atmosphere is opaque to thermal radiation from the Earth's surface.
All radiation leaving the Earth's surface is absorbed by CO$_2$ and reradiated
to upper levels of the atmosphere. 
Eventually, in the upper atmosphere, the atmosphere gets thin enough that 
CO$_2$ can radiate energy directly into space. 
When CO$_2$ is added to the atmosphere, it traps radiation leaving the Earth
at higher and higher levels of the atmosphere.
However, since the atmosphere grows colder at higher elevations, the radiation into
space is less effective than at lower elevations. 
We are essentially adding radiation shields to the upper atmosphere. 
Less radiation leaving the upper atmosphere means that more heat is trapped
closer to the Earth's surface. 
Eventually the upper atmosphere will warm enough to radiate as much heat as 
is incoming from the Sun but that warming process takes a very long time.

